es (3,750 miles) under its own power</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Paying <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr></h2>\n\n<p>You normally have to pay <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> on the vehicle, accessories bought with it and any delivery or incidental charges. </p>\n\n<p>You can do this at customs or when you report the imported vehicle.</p>\n\n<p>You don’t have to pay <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re importing a second-hand vehicle and the <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> was paid in another <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://europa.eu/about-eu/countries/index_en.htm\" title=\"Countries in the EU\">EU country</a></li>\n  <li>it&rsquo;s a temporary import and you normally live in the EU</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Report an imported vehicle</h2>\n\n<p>You must tell <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> you&rsquo;re importing a vehicle unless it&rsquo;s a temporary import and you&rsquo;re from the EU. </p>\n\n<p>Send <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> one of the forms below within 7 days of importing the vehicle or buying it (whichever is later). If you don&rsquo;t, you may be fined. </p>\n\n<p>If any tax is due <abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> will write telling you how much and when to pay. </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageVAT_Forms&amp;propertyType=document&amp;id=HMCE_CL_000059\" title=\"Form VAT 415\"><abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> 415</a> - for individuals personally importing an <abbr title=\"New Means of Transport\">NMT</abbr></li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageVAT_Forms&amp;propertyType=document&amp;id=HMCE_CL_000051\" title=\"Form VAT 414\"><abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> 414</a> - for non-NMTs or commercial imports</li>\n  <li>BFG 414 - for vehicles acquired by British Forces Germany personnel (see <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://customs.hmrc.gov.uk/channelsPortalWebApp/channelsPortalWebApp.portal?_nfpb=true&amp;_pageLabel=pageLibrary_ShowContent&amp;propertyType=document&amp;id=HMCE_CL_000165#P156_13341\" title=\"New Means of Transport: HMRC\"><abbr title=\"HM Revenue &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>&rsquo;s advice on NMTs, part 4</a>)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Vehicle tax</h2>\n\n<p>You must pay <a href=\"/vehicle-tax-rate-tables\" title=\"Vehicle tax rate tables\">vehicle tax</a> from the date your vehicle is first registered in the UK.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/importing-vehicles-into-the-uk/vat-duty-and-tax-vehicles-from-outside-the-eu","slug":"vat-duty-and-tax-vehicles-from-outside-the-eu","order":4,"title":"VAT, duty and tax: vehicles from outside the EU","body":"<h2>If you&rsquo;re moving to the UK</h2>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t pay <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> or duty on vehicles imported from outside the EU if you qualify for transfer of residence relief. To qualify you must meet these conditions: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re moving your normal home to the UK</li>\n  <li>your normal home was outside the EU for a continuous period of at least 12 months</li>\n  <li>you’ve owned and used the vehicle for at least 6 months outside the EU</li>\n  <li>you didn&rsquo;t get the vehicle under a duty or tax-free scheme</li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re going to keep the vehicle for your personal use for at least 12 months</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To get the relief, fill out form <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kb5/hmrc/forms/view.page?record=cwjlXbaGs7Q&amp;formid=98\" title=\"Form C104A\">form C104A</a> and give it to Customs when you enter the country. </p>\n\n<h2>Importing previously exported vehicles</h2>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t pay duty or <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> on vehicles imported from outside the EU if the vehicle was previously exported out of the EU. This is known as &lsquo;returned goods relief&rsquo;. To qualify you must meet these conditions:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you exported the vehicle outside the EU within the last 3 years</li>\n  <li>the taxes were paid on the vehicle in the EU and not refunded when it was exported</li>\n  <li>the vehicle hasn’t been altered outside the EU, other than necessary running repairs</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To get the relief, drive your vehicle through the ‘green channel’. You must have proof that:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the vehicle was exported</li>\n  <li>you were the person who exported it</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Non-EU registered vehicles</h2>\n\n<p>You don&rsquo;t pay duty or <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> on vehicles imported from outside the EU if it&rsquo;s registered to a non-EU resident and: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re not an EU resident </li>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re importing the vehicle temporarily for your own private use</li>\n  <li>you don&rsquo;t sell, lend or hire it within the EU </li>\n  <li>you re-export it from the EU within 6 months - you get longer if you&rsquo;re a student or on an assignment lasting a specific amount of time</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>This is known as &lsquo;temporary admission relief&rsquo;. You don’t need to contact HM Revenue &amp; Customs (<abbr title=\"HM Revenues &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>) to get the relief. However, completing <a href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kb5/hmrc/forms/view.page?record=i-925dmh8yY&amp;formId=111 “Form C110: Notice of arrival of a private motor vehicle”\" rel=\"external\">form C110</a> can help customs identify you.</p>\n\n<h3>Paying <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> or duty</h3>\n\n<p>If you don’t qualify for a relief, you must pay <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> or duty. Fill in one of the forms below and send to <abbr title=\"HM Revenues &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>form C&amp;E 386 - for individuals personally importing a vehicle </li>\n  <li>form C&amp;E 384 - for importing a vehicle for private use from outside the EU</li>\n  <li><a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kb5/hmrc/forms/view.page?record=lty64uaaaqo&amp;formId=256\" title=\"Form C&amp;E 389\">form C&amp;E 389</a> - for commerical imports </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You can ask <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://search2.hmrc.gov.uk/kbroker/hmrc/contactus/search.ladv?sr=0&amp;as=1&amp;cs=ISO-8859-1&amp;sc=hmrc&amp;sf=&amp;sm=0&amp;nh=50&amp;ha=34&amp;tx0=49682&amp;fl0=__dsid:&amp;tx1=2037&amp;raction=view\" title=\"Contact HMRC's excise and customs helpline\"><abbr title=\"HM Revenues &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> for C&amp;E 386.</a> </p>\n\n<p>Once any duty and <abbr title=\"Value Added Tax\">VAT</abbr> has been paid, <abbr title=\"HM Revenues &amp; Customs\">HMRC</abbr> will send you a form that lets you register the vehicle with the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (<abbr title=\"Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency\">DVLA</abbr>).</p>\n\n<h2>Vehicle tax</h2>\n\n<p>You’ll have to pay <a href=\"/vehicle-tax-rate-tables\" title=\"Vehicle tax rate tables\">vehicle tax</a> from the date your vehicle is first registered in the UK.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/importing-vehicles-into-the-uk/registering-an-imported-vehicle","slug":"registering-an-imported-vehicle","order":5,"title":"Registering an imported vehicle","body":"<p>If you&rsquo;re importing a vehicle into the UK permanently, you&rsquo;ll need to register it.</p>\n\n<p>You must follow all the instructions for <a href=\"/vehicle-registration/new-registrations\" title=\"New registrations\">registering a new vehicle</a>. In addition, you’ll need to include with your application:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>proof of <a href=\"/importing-vehicles-into-the-uk/mutual-recognition\" title=\"Mutual recognition\">&lsquo;Mutual Recognition&rsquo;</a> or <a href=\"/vehicle-approval\" title=\"Vehicle type approval\">type approval</a> or an exemption from it</li>\n  <li>if the vehicle i